@@ -571,6 +573,17 @@ # never: AskUserQuestion("should I create the worktree?") on obviously in-scope
 
 **When in doubt, do the work.** A tiny PR adding the fix alongside the main change is always preferable to a stand-alone ticket that lives in the backlog for weeks.
 
+**Never punt resolvable work back to the user as a "decision/data you must provide" (Non-Negotiable).** "It needs X" is almost never a reason to ask — it is a to-do list for the agent. Finding or creating a test fixture, pinning an id, checking or enabling a feature flag, doing a write in a DEV/test environment, querying a database, locating config, deciding a trade-off by running CI — that is the agent's job to ABSORB, not to surface. Before writing "this needs your decision/data," ask: _can I get it myself_ (query, search, create the fixture, check the flag, read the config, run the test)? If yes — do it; do not ask.
+
+Escalate to the user ONLY for something **genuinely user-only**, and only with evidence you already tried:
+
+- a **fact you cannot obtain** — a private URL/endpoint, the intended audience, a credential, a value that lives only in the user's head;
+- **authorization for an irreversible or outward-facing action** — a publish, a customer-facing MR merge, a money movement, a destructive op (per the always-gated rules);
+- a real access/deploy wall hit AFTER actually trying, proven (e.g. "verified branch X not deployed to env Y via Z");
+- a true product/judgment call that is the maintainer's to make.
+
+Distrust a sub-agent's "needs user decision" framing — re-test whether it is actually resolvable before relaying it. Punting resolvable work reads as helplessness; the user pays the agent to absorb the work, not to surface it.
+
 **Bundle Bugs Found Mid-Session into the Current PR (Non-Negotiable when in `auto` mode).**
 
 When you encounter a bug, broken behavior, or rough edge during any session — fix it on the spot, in the current PR if at all reasonable. Do not narrate the finding as a deferral, do not propose filing tickets, do not ask "should I fix this in a separate PR?" before doing the obvious work. Work unattended.
@@ -629,6 +642,8 @@ ## Ask About Auth Before External Service Integrations
 
 When implementing features that require an external service (Notion, Slack, CI, etc.), ask "how do you authenticate with this service?" BEFORE writing any code. The answer (direct API token, CLI auth, MCP tool, OAuth, etc.) determines the entire architecture. Skipping this question leads to multiple implementation pivots.
 
+**Zero user effort when the user says "I do nothing."** "I do nothing" / "do it yourself" / "the skill should handle it by itself" is a hard constraint on the SOLUTION SHAPE, not a preference. Acceptable user effort is **zero** — no app registration, no authorizing in a browser, no pasting client IDs/secrets/codes, no config edits. A solution that offloads setup onto the user violates the constraint even when it is technically "better" (e.g. OAuth refresh tokens). Favour mechanisms the agent can drive autonomously end to end — browser automation against an already-logged-in session, credentials cached in the secret store, auto-refresh on a 401 — and absorb the complexity rather than handing it back. Only if genuinely no zero-effort path exists, say so plainly and ask; never silently pick a high-effort path.
+
 ## Never Change PR Base Branch or Dependencies (Non-Negotiable)
 
 When a PR targets a non-default branch, that is intentional — it means the PR is part of a dependency chain. **Never** change a PR's target branch, rebase it onto a different base, or remove PR dependencies without explicit user instruction.
@@ -1002,6 +1017,25 @@ ## Escalate Honesty-Critical Verification to the Most-Honest Model
 
 The escalation is **situational and auto-clears** — it is NOT a standing reviewer-model change. It is session-scoped, idempotent (re-firing the same trigger is a no-op), and bounded by a 6-hour safety-net TTL; the primary clear is an honest, verified-complete landing (a fully-passed rubric grade). Rationale: models learn honesty over time, so the most-honest model is the right one to _verify_ a moment the agent's own honesty is in question. The firing is yours to judge (it is prompt-level, SDK-portable — not a CLI-only flag); the consequence (raise → kill-switch → auto-clear) is deterministic. Trigger #4 also has a deterministic backstop: when the rubric done-gate refuses a merge, it records the `shipped_incomplete` escalation for you.
 
+## Read Before Overwriting a Tracked Config/Dotfile (Non-Negotiable)
+
+A config/dotfile under git (`.claude/settings.json`, `.teatree.toml`, a shell rc, any dotfile) almost always carries uncommitted working-tree edits that are MORE current than `HEAD` — that is the normal state of a live dotfiles repo. Restoring the committed version over those edits is silent data loss with no recovery unless they were staged.
+
+- Treat **uncommitted > committed** by default for a config/dotfile. Never assume `HEAD` is the source of truth for a live config file.
+- Before ANY operation that replaces a tracked config/dotfile's whole content — `git checkout <path>`, `git restore <path>`, `git reset --hard`, `git stash` (it shelves the working tree), or a full-file `Write` that rewrites the file — **read the current working-tree content first**, diff it against what you are about to write, and confirm the loss is intended.
+- Prefer a **surgical `Edit`** (change only the lines you mean to) over a whole-file rewrite. Whole-file replacement is what destroys data; targeted edits do not.
+- If you must restore from git, snapshot the current content aside first (`cp <file> <file>.bak`) so the working-tree version is recoverable.
+
+This is hook-enforced, not a remembered preference. The `PreToolUse` gate `handle_block_config_overwrite` (bare sibling module `hooks/scripts/config_overwrite_guard.py`, pure logic in `teatree.core.gates.config_overwrite_guard`) BLOCKS a `git checkout`/`restore`/`reset --hard`/`stash` or a full-file `Write` that would clobber a tracked config/dotfile with uncommitted changes. Scope is narrow (`.claude/*`, `.teatree.toml`, dotfiles, known config basenames) so normal source-file git ops are untouched. Never-lockout: a per-call `[config-overwrite-ok: <reason>]` token and the `[teatree] config_overwrite_gate_enabled = false` kill-switch both ALLOW; the deny routes through `_fail_open_or_deny`.
+
+## On an Ambiguous Directive, Take the Non-Destructive Reading (Non-Negotiable)
+
+When a directive could mean two things and one reading triggers a destructive or irreversible action — killing in-flight work, deleting, overwriting, restoring from git, a destructive DB op — default to the **non-destructive** reading, or ask a neutral clarifying question that does NOT bake in the destructive option.
+
+- Never frame an `AskUserQuestion` whose every option presupposes the destructive interpretation. Always offer "do nothing / let it continue" as a real option.
+- Speed on reversible work, caution on irreversible work. Under a burst of simultaneous requests, batch-acknowledge but DELAY irreversible actions until the intent is certain — "act fast" must never resolve an ambiguous term toward the interpretation that destroys work.
+- A wrong guess on an irreversible action cannot be cheaply undone; the cost of one clarifying round-trip is far lower than the cost of recovering destroyed work.
+
 ## Re-Validate a Reused Guard in a New Destructive Context
 
 A guard or classifier that is safe for gating one action is not automatically safe for authorizing another. Before reusing an existing guard to authorize a NEW destructive operation (`git reset --hard`, force-delete, force-push, `DROP`/`DELETE`), re-validate that the guard's safety property actually holds for THIS operation — e.g. subject-matching is sufficient to clean up a forge-merged branch, but only content-equivalence (patch-id) is safe before resetting a branch. In a sub-agent brief, never assert a safety property you have not verified; require the implementer to prove the property holds in the new context, and route any change that introduces a destructive operation through an adversarial review that specifically attacks the data-loss path.
